courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of this course, participants should be able to:

1. understand recent school management reforms in Hong Kong and their impacts on preschools and kindergartens;
2. examine various roles of early childhood teachers in relation to school reforms and school-based management;
3. have basic understanding of various leadership and school management concepts and their application in daily operation of early childhood education institutions;
4. identify areas and directions for school improvement based on information gathered from annual school self-evaluation and external school review;
5. critically reflect on individual competency and school practices by linking theories and practices in the context of early childhood education.

After the course, students will be able to:

1. acquired understanding of parents’ role in children education;
2. develop awareness of ways to enhance home school communication;
3. improve parental involvement in school activities and school governance; and (4)

4. acquired practical strategies in building trust relationship with parents and mobilizing community resources.

1. Understand the nature of aesthetic experience and its role in the early years of development;
2. Understand the interrelated development of empathetic understanding, imagination, and creativity through the arts;
3. Become familiar with different forms of art and their richness;
4. Demonstrate the ability to design activities for young children in order to enhance children's appreciation and creative expressions of arts; 5.deepen their own experience of play as an ideal form for creative expressions;
5. Cultivate their creativity through the process of working on the group project and the individual essay; and
6. Enhance their sensitivity to practical issues related to the aesthetic experience and creative expressions of a young child in the local context.

At the end of the course, students should be able to demonstrates:

1. the understanding of the purposes, characteristics, and limitations of different kinds of assessments for young children, and the principles and ethics of appropriate assessment;
2. become familiar with a variety of formal and informal assessment methods, including interviewing, observation, standardized testing, and alternative assessment;
3. develop knowledge of a repertoire of effective assessment methods that can be used to continuously monitor children’s progress in different areas of learning and development; and

4. acquire a working knowledge of basic measurement concepts, including reliability, validity, norm-referenced, criterion-referenced, and standardization.

1. Learn independently;
2. Build understanding of an issue of child development;
3. Examine the issue from different perspectives

4. Develop reflective and communication skills.

After taking this course, students will be able to –

i. apply knowledge and skills in child development to practical situation of the early childhood sector;
ii. effectively perform duties at the internship site in a professional manner;
iii. develop effective communication and problem solving skills for personal and career development;
iv. reflect on personal and professional development based on the learning experience; and

v. identify their interests in future career pursuit.
